'''Joe Zen Robert Bell''' (born 27 April 1999) is a New Zealand professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[defensive midfielder]] for [[Eliteserien]] club [[Viking FK|Viking]] and the [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand national team]].

==Early and personal life==
Bell was born in [[Bristol]], England but holds dual British and New Zealand citizenship. He was raised in [[Wānaka]]<ref name="Phoenix">{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title=Norwegian club Viking FK makes play for New Zealand under-20 captain Joe Bell |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/113511057/norwegian-club-viking-stavanger-makes-play-for-under20-captain-joe-bell |access-date=15 November 2019 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=17 June 2019}}</ref> and [[Christchurch]], attending [[Medbury School]]<ref>{{ cite web|title = "Play the Game" Medbury Magazine|url=https://www.medbury.school.nz/assets/site/Play-the-Game-Spring_2021.pdf |access-date=26 August 2021 }}</ref> and [[Christ's College, Christchurch]]<ref>{{cite web |title="In Black and White" Christ's College Magazine |url=https://christscollege.com/assets/in-black-and-white_issue-55.pdf |access-date=26 August 2021 }}</ref> before moving aged 15 to Wellington to attend [[Scots College, Wellington|Scots College]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Player Testimonials |url=http://www.scotscollege.school.nz/college-football/player-testimonials/ |website=[[Scots College, Wellington|Scots College]] |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref> and play for the Phoenix.<ref name="VC Profile">{{cite web |title=Joe Bell Profile |url=https://virginiasports.com/sports/mens-soccer/roster/joe-bell/6722 |website=[[Virginia Cavaliers men's soccer]] |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>

He started playing football as an eight-year-old for [[Ferrymead Bays]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rattue |first1=Chris |title=World Cup dream only one step away |work=Star News |publisher=Star Media Network |date=15 April 2022 |pages=28–29}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Wellington Phoenix Reserves===
Bell moved to Wellington to join the Wellington Phoenix Academy under the guidance of Jess Ibrom where he started playing for the [[Wellington Phoenix FC Reserves|Wellington Phoenix Reserves]] in the [[New Zealand Football Championship]] for the [[2014–15 New Zealand Football Championship|2014–15]] season, playing 12 games with four starts.<ref name="soccerway">{{Soccerway|joe-bell/388939|access-date=25 October 2021}}</ref> He played for the reserves for another two seasons, appearing 14 times in the [[2015–16 New Zealand Football Championship|2015–16]] season with 10 starts and eight times with six starts in the [[2016–17 New Zealand Football Championship|2016–17]] season.<ref name="soccerway" /> With the New Zealand football championship played over the summer, Bell played for [[Wellington United]] in the [[Central Premier League|Central League]] during the winter.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wellington Phoenix Academy Players Shine In Capital Premier |url=https://www.wellingtonphoenix.com/news/wellington-phoenix-academy-players-shine-capital-premier |website=[[Wellington Phoenix FC]] |date=4 April 2015 |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>

===Virginia Cavaliers===
Bell joined the [[Virginia Cavaliers men's soccer|Virginia Cavaliers]] who play in the [[College soccer in the United States|NCAA Division I]] in the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]]. Bell started 55 straight games since joining the university.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bell Called into New Zealand Full National Team for International Friendlies |url=https://virginiasports.com/news/2019/11/13/mens-soccer-bell-called-up-to-new-zealand-national-team.aspx |website=[[Virginia Cavaliers men's soccer]] |date=13 November 2019 |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref> He scored six goals and had ten assists across three seasons, while also spending time with amateur club [[Charlottesville Alliance FC|Charlottesville Alliance]] during the [[2018 NPSL season]].<ref name="VC Profile" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.c-ville.com/semi-pro-soccer/|title = Charlottesville's semi-pro soccer team is a winning endeavor | date=August 2018 }}</ref>

Following his successful [[2019 FIFA U-20 World Cup|FIFA U-20 World Cup]] campaign, Bell drew the interest of several European sides, trialing with [[Eliteserien]] side [[Viking FK|Viking]] and eventually being offered a contract. However, with the [[University of Virginia]] offering him a full scholarship at year's end, Bell decided to delay going professional to get his degree.<ref name="Phoenix" /><ref>{{cite news |title=New Zealand under-20 captain Joe Bell turns down Viking FK's offer |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/nz-teams/113780386/new-zealand-under20-captain-joe-bell-turns-down-viking-fks-offer |access-date=15 November 2019 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=26 June 2019}}</ref>

Bell had a successful 2019 season with the Cavaliers as co-captain of the team which won the [[Atlantic Coast Conference#Sports|ACC Coastal Division]] and won the [[2019 ACC Men's Soccer Tournament|ACC men's tournament]] for the first time since 2009. The team ended the season winning 21 games, which was one shy of a school record.<ref>{{cite web |title=Curtain Falls on Extraordinary Season |url=https://virginiasports.com/news/2019/12/16/jeff-white-college-cup-final.aspx |website=University of Virginia Athletics |date=16 December 2019 |access-date=17 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The Cavaliers entered the [[2019 NCAA Division I Men's Soccer Tournament|2019 NCAA Tournament]] as the No. 1 seed. After wins over [[Campbell Fighting Camels and Lady Camels|Campbell]], [[St. John's Red Storm men's soccer|St. John's]], [[SMU Mustangs men's soccer|SMU]] and [[Wake Forest Demon Deacons men's soccer|Wake Forest]], Virginia lost in the final to [[Georgetown Hoyas men's soccer|Georgetown]] finishing runner up for the second time in school history.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/12/15/college-cup-soccer-georgetown-outlasts-virginia-penalty-kicks-win-its-first-ncaa-championship/ |title=College Cup soccer: Georgetown outlasts Virginia in penalty kicks to win its first NCAA title |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=15 December 2019 |newspaper=The Washington Post |access-date=16 December 2019 }}</ref> Bell ended the season playing 21 games of which he started all 21 of them, only missing two games during the ACC tournament while on International duty. He scored seven goals, of which four came during the NCAA tournament, as well as had four assists.<ref>{{cite web |title=Joe Bell – Men's Soccer |url=https://virginiasports.com/sports/mens-soccer/roster/joe-bell/6722 |website=University of Virginia Athletics |access-date=17 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>

Bell also won a number of awards both on the field and academic, including [[United Soccer Coaches#Awards programs|United Soccer Coaches]] Scholar Player of the Year, [[List of NCAA Division I men's soccer First-Team All-America teams|First Team Scholar All-American]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Bell Named United Soccer Coaches Scholar Player of the Year |url=https://virginiasports.com/news/2019/12/18/mens-soccer-bell-named-united-soccer-coaches-scholar-player-of-the-year.aspx |website=University of Virginia Athletics |date=18 December 2019 |access-date=19 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> [[2019 Atlantic Coast Conference men's soccer season#All-ACC awards and teams|ACC First Team]] and [[2019 Atlantic Coast Conference men's soccer season#All-ACC awards and teams|ACC Midfielder of the Year]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Bell Collects Scholar All-Region Honors |url=https://virginiasports.com/news/2019/12/16/mens-soccer-bell-collects-scholar-all-region-honors.aspx |website=University of Virginia Athletics |date=16 December 2019 |access-date=17 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> He was also one of three finalists for the [[Hermann Trophy|MAC Hermann Trophy]] for best player in the country.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bell Named a Finalist for the MAC Hermann Trophy |url=https://virginiasports.com/news/2019/12/12/mens-soccer-bell-named-a-finalist-for-the-mac-hermann-trophy.aspx |website=University of Virginia Athletics |date=12 December 2019 |access-date=17 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>

===Viking===
On 10 January 2020, Bell signed a three-year contract with [[Viking FK|Viking]] in the Norwegian [[Eliteserien]].<ref>{{cite news |title=All Whites midfielder Joe Bell to join Norwegian club Viking FK |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/118648866/all-whites-midfielder-joe-bell-to-join-norwegian-club-viking-fk |publisher=Stuff (website) |date=8 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Her er Vikings nysignering Joe Bell på plass|url=https://www.aftenbladet.no/sport/i/BR2pE0/Her-er-Vikings-nysignering-Joe-Bell-pa-plass|website=www.aftenbladet.no|publisher=Stavanger Aftenblad|access-date=10 January 2020|language=no|date=10 January 2020}}</ref>

===Brøndby IF===
On transfer deadline day, 31 January 2022, Bell signed a four-and-a-half-year contract with reigning [[Danish Superliga]] champions [[Brøndby IF]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Brøndby IF skriver kontrakt med Joe Bell |url=https://brondby.com/nyheder/herrer/2022/januar/brondby-if-skriver-kontrakt-med-joe-bell |publisher=Brøndby IF (website) |date=1 February 2022 |language=da}}</ref>

=== Return to Viking ===
On 29 August 2023, Bell returned to Viking, signing a four-year contract with the club.<ref>{{Cite web |date=29 August 2023 |title=Joe Bell returnerer til klubben: – Fantastisk å være tilbake |trans-title=Joe Bell returns to the club – Fantastic to be back |url=https://www.vikingfotball.no/nyheter/joe-bell-returnerer-til-klubben--fantastisk-a-vaere-tilbake |access-date=29 August 2023 |website=Viking FK |language=nb-no}}</ref> He was named in the Eliteserien Team of the Year as Viking won the [[2025 Eliteserien]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tv2.no/sport/fotball/eliteserien/forbloffet-ekspertene-ingen-hadde-sett-for-seg-det/18336564/|title=Forbløffet ekspertene: – Ingen hadde sett for seg det|work=TV 2|first=Vemund Hansen|last=Rognstad|language=no|date=1 December 2025|access-date=7 February 2026}}</ref><ref name="NRK1"/>

==International career==
===U17===
Bell was selected for the [[New Zealand national under-17 football team|New Zealand U17 national team]] that played in the [[2015 FIFA U-17 World Cup]] in Chile.<ref>{{cite web |title=FIFA U-17 World Cup Chile 2015 List of Players |url=https://www.fifadata.com/document/FU17/2015/pdf/FU17_2015_SquadLists.pdf |website=FIFA |access-date=15 November 2019 |archive-date=3 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191103180706/https://www.fifadata.com/document/FU17/2015/pdf/FU17_2015_SquadLists.pdf |url-status=dead }}</ref> He played in two of the group games, a 0–0 draw with [[Syria national under-17 football team|Syria]]<ref>{{cite web |title=New Zealand, Syria left to settle for point |url=https://static.fifa.com/u17worldcup/matches/round=271783/match=300298368/match-report.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190628215352/https://static.fifa.com/u17worldcup/matches/round=271783/match=300298368/match-report.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=28 June 2019 |website=[[FIFA]] |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref> and a 2–1 win over [[Paraguay national under-17 football team|Paraguay]].<ref>{{cite web |title=New Zealand leave it late against ten-man Paraguay |url=https://static.fifa.com/u17worldcup/matches/round=271783/match=300298363/match-report.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115022425/https://static.fifa.com/u17worldcup/matches/round%3D271783/match%3D300298363/match-report.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 November 2019 |website=FIFA |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref> As well as their loss to Brazil in the Round of 16 with a stoppage-time penalty seeing them eliminated from the competition.<ref>{{cite web |title=Brazil edge past resolute New Zealand |url=https://static.fifa.com/u17worldcup/matches/round=271781/match=300298408/match-report.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190628215412/https://static.fifa.com/u17worldcup/matches/round=271781/match=300298408/match-report.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=28 June 2019 |website=FIFA |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>

===U20===
Bell has played for and captained the [[New Zealand national under-20 football team|New Zealand U20 national team]]. Playing in the [[2018 OFC U-19 Championship]] where he was the tournament MVP and they qualified for the [[2019 FIFA U-20 World Cup]] in Poland. He has also played and captained the team at the [[2017 FIFA U-20 World Cup]] in South Korea.<ref name="soccerway" />

===Senior===
Bell made his team debut for the [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand senior national team]] in a friendly against [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Ireland]], starting in a 3–1 loss.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Voerman |first1=Andrew |title=Callum McCowatt scores on debut as new-look All Whites lose to Republic of Ireland |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/nz-teams/117073735/callum-mccowatt-scores-on-debut-as-newlook-all-whites-lose-to-republic-of-ireland |access-date=15 November 2019 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]}}</ref>

On 25 June 2021, Bell was called up to the New Zealand squad for the delayed [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2020 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/105080?newsfeedId=1275622| title= Squads named for Tokyo 2020| date= 25 June 2021| publisher= [[New Zealand Football]]| language= en| access-date= 25 June 2021| archive-date= 25 June 2021| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20210625021412/https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/105080?newsfeedId=1275622| url-status= dead}}</ref>

